Prompt content:

# CC PROMPT — v2.34.15 — fix(agents): prompt signature rendering + sanitizer scope + budget off-by-one + prompt snapshots

## Evidence

The v2.34.14 trace endpoint (finally built, finally working) let us inspect
the exact system prompt the model saw in operation `828c07ba`. Three
independent findings, all in one run.

### Finding 1 — kafka_consumer_lag(empty) regression, confirmed as prompt-layer

`/api/logs/operations/828c07ba.../trace` step 0 tool calls:
```
runbook_search({"query":"..."})
kafka_broker_status({})
kafka_consumer_lag({})          ← TypeError: missing 'group'
elastic_cluster_health({})
```

The system prompt (29855 chars, 10 tools exposed) contains BOTH:

1. `TOOL SIGNATURES` section at char 27374 with the correct shape:
   `kafka_consumer_lag(group: str)` — present, required arg clearly marked.

2. `KAFKA TRIAGE — STEP 0 (MANDATORY)` section at char 9591 with bare parens:
   ```
   Call 2: kafka_consumer_lag()
     → high lag in any consumer group → CONSUMER LAG PATH
     → call this REGARDLESS of kafka_broker_status result
   ```

The model follows the prescriptive example. The reference signature 18000
characters later is ignored until the TypeError response comes back, at
which point step 1 self-corrects to `kafka_consumer_lag({"group":"logstash"})`.

This is the same pattern as v2.34.13 (TRIAGE examples beat reference sections).
v2.34.9 signature injection was necessary but not sufficient — it fixes the
"tool signatures page" in the reference material, but any in-prompt call
example that contradicts it silently wins.

### Finding 2 — budget off-by-one

Same operation: `tool_call_count = 17` with investigate budget = 16. Step 6
made 2 tool calls when the parent had already used 15. No guard checked
whether the proposed batch would fit in the remaining budget; dispatch
happened for all 2, bringing total to 17.

### Finding 3 — sanitizer false positives on outbound responses

The v2.31.7 prompt injection sanitizer was designed to scrub LLM-bound
**input** (tool results going into the prompt). Somewhere it's also running
on **outbound** API response bodies, where it's both (a) doing nothing useful
and (b) corrupting debugging output:

```
GET /api/health       → "version": "[BLOCKED: JWT token]"        (for "2.34.14")
GET /trace            → "tokens_total": "[BLOCKED: Sensitive key]" (for an int)
GET /session/{uuid}   → body = "[BLOCKED: Sensitive key]"           (for a UUID)
```

The patterns are too loose (match on `\d+\.\d+\.\d+`, any long integer, any
UUID-shaped hex) and the scope is wrong (responses to the browser are not
the LLM attack surface).

### Meta-finding — no way to review prompt changes

Every bug this week (v2.34.13, v2.34.14, v2.34.15) has been a prompt-layer
bug masquerading as an agent-layer bug. There is no snapshot of the rendered
RESEARCH/STATUS/ACTION prompts committed to the repo, so PRs that touch
`api/agents/router.py` can silently change what the model sees without any
diff surfaced in review. Today's fix adds a snapshot-and-diff CI guard so
the next class of prompt regressions is visible at PR time.

Version bump: 2.34.14 → 2.34.15 (multiple subsystems: prompt rendering,
sanitizer, budget check, CI — architectural).

